===Etymology===
From {{etyl|goh|de}} {{m|goh|zwei}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|de}} {{m|gem-pro|*twai}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|de}} {{m|ine-pro|*dwóh₁}}. Compare Dutch {{m|nl|twee}}, English {{m|en|two}}, {{m|en|twain}}. In Old High German, and still today in some dialects, distinct forms are used for the three grammatical genders. ''Zwei'' is the originally neuter form, now used for all genders. The Old High German masculinum {{m|goh|zwēne}} is found back in early modern German {{m|de|zween}}; the femininum {{m|goh|zwō}} lives on in the variant {{m|de|zwo}} (but now without any gender distinction).

